  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Climate and Meteorological Service Advancement in Ethiopia (AHMESA-E)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Expected significant change of the project:

&#x2022; Development of comprehensive national framework on climate services. This framework will help provide strategic guidance on how various actors in the climate services domain will come together and contribute in a coordinated fashion. It will also define the users of climate information and related feedback mechanisms.  

&#x2022; Knowledge and evidence base for advancing agro-hydro meteorological services improvement. This will provide objectively verified information on the strengths and weaknesses of current climate services, as well as what is required to further advance agro-hydrological services. 

&#x2022;Establishment and fostering of stakeholder learning and dialogue platforms on climate services. This will ensure stakeholders at national, regional and woreda level can interact, share lessons and influence systems developed to ensure their effectiveness, efficiency and sustainability.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project is working towards the establishment of a National Framework for Climate Services in Ethiopia together with the National Meteorological Agency of Ethiopia, Farm Africa and Mercy Corps. The project has 3 main out put areas. Namely;   
&#x2022; Development of a National Climate Services Framework that will define a shared vision and strategic direction for; Achieving a coherent system; diversifying climate information packages available, and mainstreaming climate information packages in to agricultural and pastoral extension systems.
&#x2022;Supporting and facilitating  the development of a knowledge base for the advancement of agro-hydro meteorological services, which will input in to the further development of climate services in Ethiopia.  
&#x2022;Nurturing of stakeholder dialogue and learning platforms at national and sub-national levels which bring together government, NGOs, academia, research institutions and private sector actors as active and valued partners in defining improved climate services in Ethiopia.</narrative>
  </description>
